Analysis of Global YouTube Statistics¶

Summer 2024 Data Science Project¶

Team Members: Jay Desai, Daniel Deutsch, Aryan Choudhary¶

Introduction¶

Over the years, YouTube has established itself as a hub for content creators, enabling them to share their videos and connect with audiences on a global scale. The platform's reach is unparalleled, with millions of channels across the world offering content across all types of genres for billions of users. For content creators, marketers, and analysts, understanding the factors that influence video views and earnings is crucial. This knowledge can help content creators tailor their content to attract and retain viewers, optimize their engagement, and ultimately maximize their revenue.

The main goal of this project is to explore the relationship between YouTube video views, earnings, and various channel categories across different countries. We aim to understand if there is a significant difference in views based on the category of content and whether location impacts these metrics. By analyzing this data, we can provide insights into how content creators can optimize their channels for better engagement and monetization.

Data Cleaning¶

From the information above, we can notice that there are 28 columns. Three of the columns are created_year, created_month, and created_date. We can combine these three columns into one simply called date in datetime format.

In [ ]:
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

pd.options.mode.copy_on_write = False
df = df.dropna(subset=["created_year", "created_month", "created_date"])
df['year'] = df['created_year'].astype(int).astype(str)
df['month'] = df['created_month']
df['day'] = df['created_date'].astype(int).astype(str)

df = df.dropna(subset = ['year', 'month', 'day'])
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['year'] + ' ' + df['month'] + ' ' + df['day'])

df = df.drop(columns = ['created_year', 'year', 'created_month', 'month', 'created_date', 'day'])

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

model = LinearRegression()

# We can separate the data into rows that are filled vs rows that are null

test = df[df['video_views_for_the_last_30_days'].isnull()]

Correlation Analysis¶

Next, we are going to do correlation analysis. We want to examine the relationship between the most important variables in our dataset. In this case, examining the relationship between these variables can help us determine the most important factors related to video views, subscribers and earnings.

Calculate Median Monthly Earnings¶

To do this, we first calculate the median of lowest_monthly_earnings and highest_monthly_earnings for each row in our dataframe by applying the median() function. The resulting median values are then stored in a new column named median_monthly_earnings.

In [ ]:
df['median_monthly_earnings'] = df[['lowest_monthly_earnings', 'highest_monthly_earnings']].median(axis=1)
Calculate Correlation Matrix¶

Next, we create a correlation matrix for the columns median_monthly_earnings, subscribers, and video views using the corr() function.

In [ ]:
correlation_earnings = df[['median_monthly_earnings', 'subscribers', 'video views']].corr()
Plot Correlation Matrix¶

  • Subscribers and Video Views: A strong positive correlation (0.75) indicates that channels with more subscribers tend to have higher video views.
  • Median Monthly Earnings and Video Views: A moderately positive correlation (0.55) suggests that channels with higher video views tend to have higher mean monthly earnings.

Hypothesis Testing¶

We can perform hypothesis testing to see if there are significant differences in video views based on the category of the channel.

  • $H_{0}$: There is no significant difference in video views between different categories.
  • $H_{A}$: There is a significant difference in video views between different categories.
Visualization for Hypothesis Testing¶

We want to create a plot that will help us visualize the distribution of video views across different categories. We will do this using a box plot.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x = 'category', y ='video views', data = df)
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.title('Video Views by Category')
plt.show()
Performing ANOVA Test¶

To analyze our data, we want to perform an ANOVA test. We will do this by first retrieving unique and non-null categories from our dataset.

In [ ]:
categories = df['category'].dropna().unique()
Grouping Video Views by Category¶

Next, we need to group video views by category. We can do this by creating a list of video views by category.

In [ ]:
views_by_category = [df[df['category'] == category]['video views'].dropna() for category in categories]
Calculating the F statistic and P value¶
In [ ]:
# ANOVA test
f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(*views_by_category)
print(f'F statistic: {f_stat}')
print(f'P value: {p_val}')

F statistic: 5.071718955777486
P value: 1.0740051301004631e-10
Observations from ANOVA test¶

We conducted an ANOVA test to see if there are significant differences in video views based on the category of the channel. The results are as follows:

  • F-statistic: 5.09
  • p-value: 9.54e-11
  • Given the p-value is much smaller than the alpha value of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis, indicating significant differences in video views between categories.

Outlier Detection in Subscribers based on Video Views Using Z-Score¶

The Z-score method measures how many standard deviations a data point is from the mean. We can use this to detect outliers in the subscribers column based on their relationship with video views.

In [ ]:
# Outlier detection using z-score
df['subscribers_zscore'] = np.abs(stats.zscore(df['subscribers']))
outliers = df[df['subscribers_zscore'] >= 3]  # Z-score > 3 means it is an outlier

# Scatter Plot for Outliers in Subscribers based on Video Views
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='video views', y='subscribers', palette='viridis', hue='subscribers_zscore', size='subscribers_zscore', sizes=(20, 200))
plt.xlabel('Video Views')
plt.ylabel('Subscribers')
plt.title('Outliers in Subscribers based on Video Views')
plt.show()
In [ ]:
# Box plot without outliers
data_cleaned = df[df['subscribers_zscore'] <= 3]
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='category', y='subscribers', data=data_cleaned)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.title('Subscribers by Category Without Outliers')
plt.show()
Observations:¶
  • Adjusting for outliers will still result in data with outliers; however, by setting the z-score threshold = 3, we can remove the most extreme values from the data set.
  • Using the plot above we can see that the category with the highest median subscriber count is Trailers.
  • The category with the lowest median subscriber count is Travel & Events.

Primary analysis¶

Neural Network¶

Why We Choose Neural Network¶

  • The reason we choose the neural network model is because it can help us analyze the relationship between the success of YouTube channels via number of views, and other various factors like genre or country. By training the model on a dataset with these features, it learns patterns and makes predictions about which channels are likely to be more successful and which are not. Ultimately, this process can help us understand how different genres and regional characteristics influence a channel's success.

  • First, the model processes a variety of features including the number of subscribers, uploads, genre, country, unemployment rate, and education enrollment. By converting categorical variables like genre and country into numerical formats, the model can analyze how these different factors contribute to a channel's success.

  • Second, the neural network's structure allows it to capture complex relationships between the features and the success rate. It does this by learning from the data during the training process. The model then adjusts its internal parameters to minimize errors, allowing it to improve its ability to predict whether a channel will be successful based on the input features. This ability to learn and adapt makes the neural network a good tool for identifying the key factors that drive success for a specific channel.

  • Third, by evaluating the model's performance, we can gain insights into which factors are most important. The precision, recall, and f1-score metrics help us understand how accurately the model makes these predictions, providing a clear picture of its effectiveness.

  • Finally, the results from the neural network model guide our understanding of how different features influence success. By analyzing the model's predictions and performance, we can identify patterns and trends that answer our initial question: how do these feature affect a YouTube channel's success?

In [ ]:
# Define the high_success_threshold_views
high_success_threshold_views = df['video views'].quantile(0.75)

# Create a binary target variable
df['high_success'] = (df['video views'] >= high_success_threshold_views).astype(int)

# Select relevant features
features = ['subscribers', 'uploads', 'category', 'Country', 'Unemployment rate', 'Gross tertiary education enrollment (%)']

# Convert categorical variables to dummy variables
data = pd.get_dummies(df[features + ['high_success']], drop_first = True)

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X = data.drop(columns = 'high_success')
y = data['high_success']

# Impute missing values (if any)
X = X.fillna(X.mean())

# Standardize the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 42)

# Convert target variable to categorical
y_train_nn = to_categorical(y_train)
y_test_nn = to_categorical(y_test)

# Define and compile the neural network model
nn_model = Sequential()
nn_model.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train.shape[1], activation='relu'))
nn_model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
nn_model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))

nn_model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'mean_squared_error', metrics = ['accuracy'])

# Train the neural network
history_nn = nn_model.fit(X_train, y_train_nn, epochs = 50, batch_size = 32, validation_spli = 0.2)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred_nn = nn_model.predict(X_test)
y_pred_classes_nn = np.argmax(y_pred_nn, axis=1)

# Evaluate the model
report_nn = classification_report(y_test, y_pred_classes_nn, output_dict = True)
conf_matrix_nn = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_classes_nn)

Visualization¶

In [ ]:
# Convert the classification report to a DataFrame
report_df = pd.DataFrame(report_nn).transpose()

# Plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(report_df.iloc[:-1, :-1], annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='.2f', cbar_kws={'label': 'Metric Value'})

# Improve the labels
plt.title('Neural Network Classification Performance')
plt.xlabel('Evaluation Metrics')
plt.ylabel('Classes/Labels')
plt.show()

  • The results of the neural network model indicate that it performs well in predicting the majority class, which in this case is the channels that are not in the high success category (Class 0). The precision for Class 0 is 0.86, meaning that when the model predicts a channel as not high success, it is correct 86% of the time.

  • The recall for Class 0 is 0.94, indicating that the model correctly identifies 94% of the actual not high success channels.

  • The f1-score, which balances precision and recall, is 0.89, demonstrating strong performance in predicting channels that are not highly successful. This suggests that the model effectively captures the characteristics of channels that do not achieve high success.

  • However, the model's performance is less robust for predicting the high success channels (Class 1). The precision for Class 1 is 0.77, which means that 77% of the channels predicted as high success are indeed high success.

  • The recall is notably lower at 0.57, indicating that the model correctly identifies only 57% of the actual high success channels.

  • The f1-score for Class 1 is 0.65, reflecting a moderate balance between precision and recall but highlighting the model's struggle to accurately identify all high success channels. This suggests that while the model can identify a lot of high success channels, it misses some of them, indicating room for improvement in capturing the characteristics that define highly successful channels.

  • The overall accuracy of the model is 0.84, meaning that it correctly predicts the success category for 84% of the channels in the test set. The macro average, which averages the precision, recall, and f1-score across both classes, and the weighted average, which takes into account the class distribution, both show that the model generally performs well but is biased towards the majority class.

  • These results suggest that the model provides useful insights into the factors influencing YouTube channel success, particularly for channels that are not highly successful.

  • This aligns with our hypothesis by demonstrating a correlation between success and the analyzed features, but highlights the need for improved sensitivity towards high success cases, possibly by addressing class imbalance and enhancing feature representation.

Insights and Conclusions¶

  • Our project aimed to create a Machine Learning model from a YouTube dataset. The model aimed to predict whether a channel would have a high or low view count based on the other statistics measured in the dataset.
  • We chose a Neural Network to implement this model. After normalizing the data and splitting into training and testing, we trained the model on the training data and tested it.
  • Our model's poorer scores for Class 1 compared to Class 0 can partly be explained by the limited number of data points with high views compared to those with low views.
  • Perhaps an expanded dataset with more high class entries, or other methods which give greater value to these cases, would improve the scores of our model for Class 1.
  • Additionally, perhaps exposure to additional features, such as subscribers over the last 30 days or uploads per week, would enhance the model.
  • Our data is limited in its ability to truly capture the nature of YouTube channels, as this is something difficult to quantify with numbers. Our model reflects these limitations, showing that there is no easy way to show what makes popular YouTubers so succesful.
